Your question has two questions.

**What is a provider?**

First, an provider is just a generic functional interface, witch should return an instance of the specified type.

For ex.:
```java
public class TestProvider implements Provider&lt;Test&gt; {

	@Override
	public Test get() {
		return new Test();
	}
}

Provider&lt;Test&gt; provider = new TestProvider();
```

or as a lamda:

```java
Provider&lt;Test&gt; provider = () -&gt; new Test();
```

**How does a scope act with a provider?**

The .in() method call specifies the scope. In this case it is a singleton. So what happens behind the scenes is, that Guice creates an provider around your provider:

```java
public class ExampleSingletonProvider implements com.google.inject.Provider&lt;Test&gt; {

	private final Provider&lt;Test&gt; testProvider;
	private Test instance;

	public ExampleSingletonProvider(Provider&lt;Test&gt; testProvider) {
		this.testProvider = testProvider;
	}

	@Override
	public Test get() {
		if (instance == null) {
			instance = testProvider.get();
		}
		return instance;
	}
}
```

This invokes the ``Provider#get()`` method once and caches its result.

